      <title>Dark patches on Venus could be signs of microbial life</title>
      <description><![CDATA[VENUS  A new study theorizes that the dark splotches on Venus may be a sign that there's life on the planet. Microbial life, that is.According to a paper published in the journal Astrobiology, climate models suggest Venus had a habitable climate and liquid water for 2 billion years, before a runaway greenhouse gas effect raised surface temperatures and turned the atmosphere toxic.The research suggests that microorganisms may be living in the planet's lower cloud layer, which has a stable temperature and more Earth-like atmospheric pressure.Dark patches on Venus could be microbial blooms made of sulfuric acid and other light-absorbing particles, which can persist for days while changing shape and contrast.Certain bacteria on Earth can survive in high altitudes after being swept into the atmosphere; others have also been known to thrive in extremely harsh environments.Thus far, the probes that have explored Venus have been incapable of distinguishing between organic and inorganic particles.So until a new contraption gets there, no one knows for sure if life does exist on the hottest planet in the solar system.]]></description>
